Quadratic Functional Encryption for Secure Training in Vertical Federated Learning

Shuangyi Chen1, Anuja Modi2, Shweta Agrawal2, and Ashish Khisti1 1University of Toronto, {shuangyi.chen@mail.utoronto.ca, akhisti@ece.utoronto.ca} 2IIT Madras, {cs21d405@cse.iitm.ac.in, shweta.a@cse.iitm.ac.in}
Abstract

Vertical federated learning (VFL) enables the collaborative training of machine learning (ML) models in settings where the data is distributed amongst multiple parties who wish to protect the privacy of their individual data. Notably, in VFL, the labels are available to a single party and the complete feature set is formed only when data from all parties is combined. Recently, Xu et al. [1] proposed a new framework called FedV for secure gradient computation for VFL using multi-input functional encryption. In this work, we explain how some of the information leakage in Xu et al. can be avoided by using Quadratic functional encryption when training generalized linear models for vertical federated learning.

I Introduction

In many emerging applications, a machine learning (ML) model must be trained using private data that is distributed among multiple parties. We study the setting of vertical federated learning (VFL) where each individual party has access to a subset of features and labels and must cooperate to train a ML model that makes use of all the features. When privacy of user data is required, homomorphic encryption (HE) [2, 3], which enables the computation on encrypted data, provides a natural solution. In recent years, there has been a significant interest in HE based VFL systems, see e.g., [5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12]. Some works such as [7, 8, 11] consider a two-party protocol without the trusted coordinator, while others [10, 9]. consider a multi-party settings. Those frameworks require a large amount of peer-to-peer communications. References [5, 6] propose frameworks comprised of one trusted coordinator, storing the global weights, and two parties, each with a subset of vertically partitioned data. However, these frameworks require the trusted coordinator to share plaintext global weights with parties, which undermines the model’s confidentiality.

In a recent work, Xu et. al. [1] proposed a generic and efficient privacy-preserving vertical Federated Learning (VFL) framework known as FedV in the multiparty setting. FedV makes use of single-input function encryption (𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SIFE}) and multi-input function encryption (𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE}), and makes the communication between the clients and the aggregator a one-round interaction. However, FedV still have some key drawbacks. The protocol can reveal more information to the aggregator than just the final gradient in each iteration. Moreover, the protocol reveals the respective updated weights in each iteration to clients, which additionally creates leakage. For more details, please see Section IV.

I-A Our Results.

We observe that the leakage created in FedV is caused by choosing an multi-input functional encryption (𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE}) scheme that only supports linear functions. Due to this, the weights are required to be provided to each party for inclusion in encryption, which creates unnecessary leakage. We observe that for linear models, this leakage can be prevented by using a more powerful 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} scheme, namely 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} for quadratic functions which can also be constructed using standard assumptions in cryptography [17, 18]. As our main contribution in this work, we demonstrate how such a function encryption scheme can be applied in VFL training by proposing a novel construction of function vectors that serve as a basis for generating decryption keys. Our approach leads to direct computation of the gradients, without leakage of any intermediate results as is the case with FedV. We discuss our proposed protocol, SFedV, for linear model training in Section IV and the extension to logistic regression model in Appendix C. We provide a thorough analysis of both security and efficiency in Section IV.

We also discuss logistic regression model in Appendix C. In each iteration of the training phase, our protocol takes as input an encrypted copy of the features \mathbold​Xit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑡\mathbold{X}_{i}^{t} and encrypted labels \mathbold​yt∈ℝS\mathboldsuperscript𝑦𝑡superscriptℝ𝑆\mathbold{y}^{t}\in\mathbb{R}^{S} from clients, and collaboratively and securely computes the gradients g​(\mathbold​wt)𝑔\mathboldsuperscript𝑤𝑡g(\mathbold{w}^{t}).

Our threat model is defined as follows: we assume the aggregator is honest-but-curious meaning it correctly follows the algorithms and protocols but will try to infer clients’ private data. Additionally, we assume that the aggregator does not collude with anyone. Similarly, the trusted third party is assumed not to collude with anyone. With respect to the clients, we assume that there are at most N−1𝑁1N-1 dishonest clients who may collude together and share their data to infer honest clients’ information.

The protocol enables all the entities to collaboratively compute the gradient using vertically partitioned data. During the training process, we aim to achieve the following privacy requirements: 1) The client i𝑖i and the aggregator should learn nothing about data \mathbold​Xj\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑗\mathbold{X}_{j} of client j𝑗j for i≠j𝑖𝑗i\neq j. 2) Any client should learn nothing about the trained global model weights \mathbold​w\mathbold𝑤\mathbold{w}, intermediate results including the prediction error as in (1) and the gradient g​(\mathbold​w)𝑔\mathbold𝑤g(\mathbold{w}). Moreover, i𝑖ith client should not learn anything about his/her own corresponding weights \mathbold​wi\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖\mathbold{w}_{i}.

III Preliminaries

III-A Functional Encryption

Functional Encryption [14, 15, 16] is a public key encryption scheme that enables fine-grained access control over the encrypted data. In Single Input Functional Encryption(𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SIFE}), the secret key is associated with a function f𝑓f, and the ciphertext is associated with the vector \mathbold​x\mathbold𝑥\mathbold{x}. The decryption of ciphertext using the secret key outputs f​(\mathbold​x)𝑓\mathbold𝑥f(\mathbold{x}). Intuitively, the security says that the adversary learns nothing about the input \mathbold​x\mathbold𝑥\mathbold{x} beyond what is revealed by {fi​(\mathbold​x)}isubscriptsubscript𝑓𝑖\mathbold𝑥𝑖\{f_{i}(\mathbold{x})\}_{i} for any set of secret keys corresponding to the functions {fi}isubscriptsubscript𝑓𝑖𝑖\{f_{i}\}_{i} that the adversary holds.

III-B Multi-Input Functional Encryption

Goldwasser et al. [13] generalized the functional encryption to support functions with multiple inputs. Multi-Input Functional Encryption, denoted as 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} supports functions with arity greater than one. In 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE}, the secret key is associated with a function f𝑓f, and the i𝑖ith ciphertext is associated with the vector \mathbold​xi\mathboldsubscript𝑥𝑖\mathbold{x}_{i} for i∈[N]𝑖delimited-[]𝑁i\in[N] where N𝑁N is the arity of the function f𝑓f. The decryption of all the ciphertexts using the secret key outputs f​(\mathbold​x1,…,\mathbold​xN)𝑓\mathboldsubscript𝑥1…\mathboldsubscript𝑥𝑁f(\mathbold{x}_{1},\ldots,\mathbold{x}_{N}). We now describe this notion in more detail.

Security. Intuitively, security says that no information about the messages can be learned by the adversary except what is revealed by virtue of functionality – in more detail, an adversary possessing some ciphertexts and secret keys can perform decryption and learn the output of the functionality, which itself leaks something about the underlying plaintext. But besides this necessary leakage, the adversary does not learn anything. We provide the formal definition of security in Appendix A.

Multi-Input FE for Quadratic Functions. Agrawal, Goyal, and Tomida [18] constructed a multi-input functional encryption for quadratic functions (𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{qMIFE}). Here ⊗tensor-product\otimes denotes the Kronecker product. A n𝑛n-input 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} scheme for the function class ℱm,nsubscriptℱ𝑚𝑛\mathcal{F}_{m,n} is defined as: each i𝑖ith client encrypts \mathbold​xi∈ℤm\mathboldsubscript𝑥𝑖superscriptℤ𝑚\mathbold{x}_{i}\in\mathbb{Z}^{m} using i𝑖ith encryption key 𝖤𝖪isubscript𝖤𝖪𝑖\mathsf{EK}_{i} to get the i𝑖ith ciphertext 𝖢𝖳isubscript𝖢𝖳𝑖\mathsf{CT}_{i} for i∈[n]𝑖delimited-[]𝑛i\in[n]. The 𝖪𝖾𝗒𝖦𝖾𝗇𝖪𝖾𝗒𝖦𝖾𝗇\mathsf{KeyGen} algorithm issues the secret key 𝖲𝖪𝖲𝖪\mathsf{SK} for \mathbold​c∈ℤ(m​n)2\mathbold𝑐superscriptℤsuperscript𝑚𝑛2\mathbold{c}\in\mathbb{Z}^{(mn)^{2}} where \mathbold​c\mathbold𝑐\mathbold{c} is the vector representation of the function f∈ℱm,n𝑓subscriptℱ𝑚𝑛f\in\mathcal{F}_{m,n}. III-C FedV

As the system model of SFedV (Section II-A), FedV involves an aggregator, N clients, and a Trusted Third Party (TTP). Each client holds a subset of features \mathbold​Xi∈ℝS×Fi\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖superscriptℝ𝑆subscript𝐹𝑖\mathbold{X}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{S\times F_{i}}, and the first client also has the corresponding labels \mathbold​y∈ℝS\mathbold𝑦superscriptℝ𝑆\mathbold{y}\in\mathbb{R}^{S} along with its subset of features. The aggregator holds the complete model weights \mathbold​w=[\mathbold​w0​||\mathbold​w1|​|…||​\mathbold​wN−1]\mathbold𝑤delimited-[]\mathboldsubscript𝑤0\mathboldsubscript𝑤1…\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑁1\mathbold{w}=[\mathbold{w}_{0}||\mathbold{w}_{1}||...||\mathbold{w}_{N-1}] where \mathbold​wi∈ℝFi\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖superscriptℝsubscript𝐹𝑖\mathbold{w}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{F_{i}} is the partial weights that pertains to \mathbold​Xi\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖\mathbold{X}_{i}. In each iteration, there are two steps to compute the gradient

g​(\mathbold​w)=−2S​[\mathbold​u⊤​\mathbold​X0∥…∥\mathbold​u⊤​\mathbold​XN−1]𝑔\mathbold𝑤2𝑆matrix∥\mathboldsuperscript𝑢top\mathboldsubscript𝑋0…\mathboldsuperscript𝑢top\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑁1\displaystyle g(\mathbold{w})=-\frac{2}{S}\begin{bmatrix}\mathbold{u}^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{0}\mathbin{\|}...\mathbin{\|}\mathbold{u}^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{N-1}\end{bmatrix} (3)

where (\mathbold​u)⊤=(\mathbold​y−\mathbold​X0​\mathbold​w0−…−\mathbold​XN−1​\mathbold​wN−1)⊤superscript\mathbold𝑢topsuperscript\mathbold𝑦\mathboldsubscript𝑋0\mathboldsubscript𝑤0…\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑁1\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑁1top(\mathbold{u})^{\top}=(\mathbold{y}-\mathbold{X}_{0}\mathbold{w}_{0}-...-\mathbold{X}_{N-1}\mathbold{w}_{N-1})^{\top}.

In the first step called Feature Dimension Secure Aggregation, FedV uses a Multi-Input Functional Encryption (𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤)𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤(\mathsf{MIFE}) scheme for the inner product functionality [19, 20] to securely compute the prediction error \mathbold​u\mathbold𝑢\mathbold{u}. In this step, the aggregator sends each i𝑖ith client the partial weights \mathbold​wi\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖\mathbold{w}_{i}. Then each i𝑖ith client encrypts each sample of (−\mathbold​Xi​\mathbold​wi)∈ℝS\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖superscriptℝ𝑆(-\mathbold{X}_{i}\mathbold{w}_{i})\in\mathbb{R}^{S} and sends the ciphertext set 𝖢𝖳−\mathbold​Xi​\mathbold​wi𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{CT}_{-\mathbold{X}_{i}\mathbold{w}_{i}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}} to the aggregator. The first client, holding the label \mathbold​y\mathbold𝑦\mathbold{y}, encrypts each sample of \mathbold​y−\mathbold​X1​\mathbold​w1\mathbold𝑦\mathboldsubscript𝑋1\mathboldsubscript𝑤1\mathbold{y}-\mathbold{X}_{1}\mathbold{w}_{1} and sends the ciphertext set 𝖢𝖳\mathbold​y−\mathbold​X1​\mathbold​w1𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathbold𝑦\mathboldsubscript𝑋1\mathboldsubscript𝑤1𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{CT}_{\mathbold{y}-\mathbold{X}_{1}\mathbold{w}_{1}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}} to the aggregator. The aggregator asks the TTP for the secret key 𝖲𝖪\mathbold​v𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖲𝖪\mathbold𝑣𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SK}_{\mathbold{v}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}} corresponding to the fusion vector \mathbold​v\mathbold𝑣\mathbold{v}. This vector \mathbold​v\mathbold𝑣\mathbold{v} can be a binary vector where one in i𝑖ith position means that the aggregator has received ciphertext from client i𝑖i. Using the secret key 𝖲𝖪\mathbold​v𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖲𝖪\mathbold𝑣𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SK}_{\mathbold{v}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}}, the aggregator decrypts the ciphertexts {{𝖢𝖳−\mathbold​Xi​\mathbold​wi𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤}i=1N−1,𝖢𝖳\mathbold​y−\mathbold​X1​\mathbold​w1𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤}superscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝑖1𝑁1superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathbold𝑦\mathboldsubscript𝑋1\mathboldsubscript𝑤1𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\{\{\mathsf{CT}_{-\mathbold{X}_{i}\mathbold{w}_{i}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}}\}_{i=1}^{N-1},\mathsf{CT}_{\mathbold{y}-\mathbold{X}_{1}\mathbold{w}_{1}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}}\} to get the prediction error \mathbold​u\mathbold𝑢\mathbold{u} (Equation (1)), which is the inner product of the fusion vector \mathbold​v\mathbold𝑣\mathbold{v} and the partial predictions from clients.

In the second step called Sample Dimension Secure Aggregation, FedV uses Single-Input Functional Encryption (𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤)𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤(\mathsf{SIFE}) scheme to compute the gradient g​(\mathbold​w)𝑔\mathbold𝑤g(\mathbold{w}). In this step, each client i𝑖i encrypts each element of \mathbold​Xi\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖\mathbold{X}_{i} and sends the ciphertext set 𝖢𝖳\mathbold​Xi𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{CT}_{\mathbold{X}_{i}}^{\mathsf{SIFE}} to the aggregator. On receiving the secret key 𝖲𝖪\mathbold​u𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖲𝖪\mathbold𝑢𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SK}_{\mathbold{u}}^{\mathsf{SIFE}} corresponding to the prediction error \mathbold​u\mathbold𝑢\mathbold{u} from TTP, the aggregator decrypts the ciphertexts to get {\mathbold​u⊤​\mathbold​Xi}i∈[N]subscript\mathboldsuperscript𝑢top\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑖delimited-[]𝑁\{\mathbold{u}^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{i}\}_{i\in[N]}. The aggregator further processes the decryption results {\mathbold​u⊤​\mathbold​Xi}i∈[N]subscript\mathboldsuperscript𝑢top\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑖delimited-[]𝑁\{\mathbold{u}^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{i}\}_{i\in[N]} according to Equation (3) to get the gradient g​(\mathbold​w)𝑔\mathbold𝑤g(\mathbold{w}). Using the gradients, the model weights are updated and then the training of the next epoch starts. Note the transmission of 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} ciphertext (𝖢𝖳\mathbold​Xi​\mathbold​wi𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{CT}_{\mathbold{X}_{i}\mathbold{w}_{i}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}} or 𝖢𝖳\mathbold​y−\mathbold​X1​\mathbold​w1𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathbold𝑦\mathboldsubscript𝑋1\mathboldsubscript𝑤1𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{CT}_{\mathbold{y}-\mathbold{X}_{1}\mathbold{w}_{1}}^{\mathsf{MIFE}}) and 𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SIFE} ciphertext (𝖢𝖳\mathbold​Xi𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖳\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑖𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{CT}_{\mathbold{X}_{i}}^{\mathsf{SIFE}}) can be simultaneous. Thus the communication between each client and the aggregator is a one-round interaction in each iteration.

Leakage in FedV. While FedV preserves each client’s data, it reveals the intermediate result, the prediction error \mathbold​u\mathbold𝑢\mathbold{u} to the aggregator. Moreover, in the Feature Dimension Secure Aggregation step, the i𝑖ith client is required to know the respective weight \mathbold​wi\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖\mathbold{w}_{i}. Additionally, the aggregator can use the secret key of t𝑡tth iteration to decrypt the ciphertext of some other iteration t′superscript𝑡′t^{\prime} for t′≠tsuperscript𝑡′𝑡t^{\prime}\neq t to infer more information about client data.

IV The Protocol

Now we introduce our protocol with Multi-input Quadratic Functional Encryption 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{qMIFE} [18] as a privacy enhancement technology to do training in VFL setting.

At the beginning of the training phase, the aggregator initializes the global weights \mathbold​w0\mathboldsuperscript𝑤0\mathbold{w}^{0} and starts training. The training phase is iterative, where in the t𝑡tth iteration, the TTP runs the 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖲𝖾𝗍𝗎𝗉formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖲𝖾𝗍𝗎𝗉\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{Setup} algorithm to get the public parameters 𝖯𝖯tsuperscript𝖯𝖯𝑡\mathsf{PP}^{t}, N𝑁N encryption keys {𝖤𝖪i}i∈[N]tsuperscriptsubscriptsubscript𝖤𝖪𝑖𝑖delimited-[]𝑁𝑡\{\mathsf{EK}_{i}\}_{i\in[N]}^{t} and a master secret key 𝖬𝖲𝖪tsuperscript𝖬𝖲𝖪𝑡\mathsf{MSK}^{t}, then delivers the encryption key EKitsuperscriptsubscriptEK𝑖𝑡\textsf{EK}_{i}^{t} to the corresponding client i𝑖i. After receiving the encryption key and determining the batch \mathbold​Xt\mathboldsuperscript𝑋𝑡\mathbold{X}^{t} used for training in this iteration, each client uses EKitsuperscriptsubscriptEK𝑖𝑡\textsf{EK}_{i}^{t} to encrypt \mathbold​xit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑥𝑖𝑡\mathbold{x}_{i}^{t} which is the vectorized \mathbold​Xit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑡{\mathbold{X}_{i}^{t}} (vec(⋅)⋅(\cdot) stacks the columns of a matrix into a vector) to get ciphertext CTitsuperscriptsubscriptCT𝑖𝑡\textsf{CT}_{i}^{t}. Each client sends CTitsuperscriptsubscriptCT𝑖𝑡\textsf{CT}_{i}^{t} to the aggregator. The client that holds the labels encrypts \mathbold​xit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑥𝑖𝑡\mathbold{x}_{i}^{t} and \mathbold​yt\mathboldsuperscript𝑦𝑡\mathbold{y}^{t} with EKitsuperscriptsubscriptEK𝑖𝑡\textsf{EK}_{i}^{t} to get ciphertexts CTitsuperscriptsubscriptCT𝑖𝑡\textsf{CT}_{i}^{t} and CT\mathbold​ytsuperscriptsubscriptCT\mathbold𝑦𝑡\textsf{CT}_{\mathbold{y}}^{t} respectively and then sends (CTit,CT\mathbold​yt)superscriptsubscriptCT𝑖𝑡superscriptsubscriptCT\mathbold𝑦𝑡(\textsf{CT}_{i}^{t},\textsf{CT}_{\mathbold{y}}^{t}) to the aggregator. At the same time, the aggregator computes a set of function vectors 𝒞tsuperscript𝒞𝑡\mathcal{C}^{t} according to the model weights \mathbold​wt\mathboldsuperscript𝑤𝑡\mathbold{w}^{t} of the current iteration and sends them to TTP to generate a set of decryption keys. Detailed procedure is described in Section IV-A. Then, the aggregator decrypts all the ciphertexts ({CTit}i=0N−1,CTyt)superscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptCT𝑖𝑡𝑖0𝑁1superscriptsubscriptCT𝑦𝑡(\{\textsf{CT}_{i}^{t}\}_{i=0}^{N-1},\textsf{CT}_{y}^{t}) that were received from clients using the secret keys received from TTP, to get each element of (2) respectively. By concatenating those elements and further processing the results, the aggregator gets the gradients. After this, it can update the global weights and start the training of the next iteration. Algorithm 1 shows the training procedure for linear models and also supports the training for logistic regression as discussed in Appendix C.

IV-B Privacy Analysis

Recall the aim of our framework. We want the client i𝑖i and the aggregator to learn nothing about data \mathbold​Xj\mathboldsubscript𝑋𝑗\mathbold{X}_{j} of client j𝑗j for i≠j𝑖𝑗i\neq j. We also want that any client should learn nothing about the trained global model weights \mathbold​w\mathbold𝑤\mathbold{w}, intermediate results including error between labels and feed-forward output as in (1) and the gradient g​(\mathbold​w)𝑔\mathbold𝑤g(\mathbold{w}). Moreover, i𝑖ith client should not learn anything about his/her own corresponding weights \mathbold​wi\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖\mathbold{w}_{i}. In this section, we prove that we have achieved the above-stated goal.

Theorem IV.1.

If Quadratic MIFE (𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤)𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤(\mathsf{qMIFE}) is secure according to definition 2, then in each training iteration t𝑡t, i𝑖ith client’s data \mathbold​Xit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑡\mathbold{X}_{i}^{t} for i∈[N]𝑖delimited-[]𝑁i\in[N] is hidden from client j𝑗j and the aggregator, trained global model weights \mathbold​wt\mathboldsuperscript𝑤𝑡\mathbold{w}^{t} and intermediate results \mathbold​ut\mathboldsuperscript𝑢𝑡\mathbold{u}^{t} as in (1) are hidden from the clients and i𝑖ith client learns nothing about weight \mathbold​wi\mathboldsubscript𝑤𝑖\mathbold{w}_{i}.

Let us fix the iteration number to be t𝑡t. In each iteration, the TTP runs the 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖲𝖾𝗍𝗎𝗉formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖲𝖾𝗍𝗎𝗉\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{Setup} algorithm to get public parameters 𝖯𝖯tsuperscript𝖯𝖯𝑡\mathsf{PP}^{t}, N𝑁N encryption keys {𝖤𝖪i}i∈[N]tsuperscriptsubscriptsubscript𝖤𝖪𝑖𝑖delimited-[]𝑁𝑡\{\mathsf{EK}_{i}\}_{i\in[N]}^{t} and a master secret key 𝖬𝖲𝖪tsuperscript𝖬𝖲𝖪𝑡\mathsf{MSK}^{t}. The clients encrypt their respective data and send the ciphertexts to the aggregator. The aggregator asks the TTP for the secret key corresponding to the set of vectors 𝒞tsuperscript𝒞𝑡\mathcal{C}^{t}. Each vector \mathbold​ci,pt\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑐𝑖𝑝𝑡\mathbold{c}_{i,p}^{t} is set in such a way that the 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖣𝖾𝖼formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖣𝖾𝖼\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{Dec} only reveals the inner product ⟨\mathbold​ci,pt,\mathbold​x⊗\mathbold​x⟩=((\mathbold​ut)⊤​\mathbold​Xit)​[p]\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑐𝑖𝑝𝑡tensor-product\mathbold𝑥\mathbold𝑥superscript\mathboldsuperscript𝑢𝑡top\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑡delimited-[]𝑝\langle\mathbold{c}_{i,p}^{t},\mathbold{x}\otimes\mathbold{x}\rangle=((\mathbold{u}^{t})^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{i}^{t})[p]. Quadratic MIFE ensures that nothing about \mathbold​Xit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋𝑖𝑡\mathbold{X}_{i}^{t} and \mathbold​ut\mathboldsuperscript𝑢𝑡\mathbold{u}^{t} is revealed to the aggregator. Moreover, each client encrypts their data using different encryption keys. The ciphertexts are indistinguishable; hence, clients cannot predict other clients’ data.

Unlike FedV, in our framework, the client runs the 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖤𝗇𝖼formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖤𝗇𝖼\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{Enc} algorithm which only takes their respective data and encryption keys as input. Hence, each client i𝑖i learns nothing about their respective weight \mathbold​wit\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑤𝑖𝑡\mathbold{w}_{i}^{t}. Moreover, Quadratic MIFE ensures that client i𝑖i learns nothing about the global weight \mathbold​wt\mathboldsuperscript𝑤𝑡\mathbold{w}^{t}. The aggregator does not share the gradients in any form with the clients. Therefore, the gradient g​(\mathbold​wt)𝑔\mathboldsuperscript𝑤𝑡g(\mathbold{w}^{t}) is also not revealed.

Importance of using new 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{qMIFE} instance for each iteration. Let in the iteration t𝑡t, the ciphertext be 𝖢𝖳tsuperscript𝖢𝖳𝑡\mathsf{CT}^{t} and secret key be 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖲𝖪tformulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscript𝖲𝖪𝑡\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{SK}^{t}. Suppose the TTP uses the same 𝖬𝖲𝖪𝖬𝖲𝖪\mathsf{MSK} to generate secret keys 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖲𝖪t+1formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscript𝖲𝖪𝑡1\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{SK}^{t+1} for some other iteration, say t+1𝑡1t+1, then the aggregator may use 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖲𝖪t+1formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscript𝖲𝖪𝑡1\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{SK}^{t+1} to decrypt the ciphertext 𝖢𝖳tsuperscript𝖢𝖳𝑡\mathsf{CT}^{t} instead of using it to decrypt the ciphertext 𝖢𝖳t+1superscript𝖢𝖳𝑡1\mathsf{CT}^{t+1}. Using this "mix-and-match" attack by performing decryptions of secret key and ciphertexts from different iterations, he will know g​(\mathbold​w)=−2S​[(\mathbold​ut+1)⊤​\mathbold​X0t​‖…‖​(\mathbold​ut+1)⊤​\mathbold​XN−1t]𝑔\mathbold𝑤2𝑆matrixsuperscript\mathboldsuperscript𝑢𝑡1top\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋0𝑡norm…superscript\mathboldsuperscript𝑢𝑡1top\mathboldsuperscriptsubscript𝑋𝑁1𝑡g(\mathbold{w})=-\frac{2}{S}\begin{bmatrix}(\mathbold{u}^{t+1})^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{0}^{t}||...||(\mathbold{u}^{t+1})^{\top}\mathbold{X}_{N-1}^{t}\end{bmatrix}.

If TTP generates different 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{qMIFE} instance for every iteration, then decryption of 𝖢𝖳tsuperscript𝖢𝖳𝑡\mathsf{CT}^{t} with secret key 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤.𝖲𝖪t+1formulae-sequence𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤superscript𝖲𝖪𝑡1\mathsf{qMIFE}.\mathsf{SK}^{t+1} will give some garbage value which will be irrelevant for the aggregator. Therefore, it is important for the TTP to generate a new 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{qMIFE} instance for every iteration.

Comparison of our framework with FedV. Unlike FedV, our framework does not leak the intermediate result \mathbold​u\mathbold𝑢\mathbold{u} to the aggregator. The global weights \mathbold​w\mathbold𝑤\mathbold{w} are kept secret from the clients and each client also learns nothing about their respective weights. In addition to this, we also ensure that the aggregator cannot use the mix-and-match attack to learn some useful information.

IV-C Efficiency Analysis

Communication. Regarding communication complexity, SFedV requires one-way client-aggregator communication, while FedV needs one-round client-aggregator communication due to the delivery of global weights by the aggregator. Additionally, SFedV uses a new 𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝗊𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{qMIFE} instance in each iteration to prevent mix-and-match attacks. Thus, an increase of communication between TTP and clients becomes necessary. Note that FedV can also prevent mix-and-match attacks by using new instances of 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} and 𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖲𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{SIFE} in each iteration. In such a scenario, the client-TTP communication complexity for each iteration will be the same for both FedV and SFedV.

Computation. Table I provides a comparison between FedV and SFedV in terms of the number of encryption and decryption processes in each iteration. The significant improvement of SFedV is attributed to the advancement of quadratic 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} and the careful design of function vectors.

In terms of the number of the vector corresponding to which the secret keys are generated, FedV uses two vectors for two steps: \mathbold​v\mathbold𝑣\mathbold{v} for feature dimension secure aggregation and \mathbold​u\mathbold𝑢\mathbold{u} for sample dimension secure aggregation. In contrast, our SFedV framework employs F𝐹F vectors \mathbold​c\mathbold𝑐\mathbold{c}, where F𝐹F is the total number of features. The increase in size can be justified by our use of a quadratic 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE} scheme instead of inner product 𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤𝖬𝖨𝖥𝖤\mathsf{MIFE}.

V Conclusions

Prior N𝑁N-party VFL framework FedV incurs information leakage which seriously undermines individual data privacy. In this work, to address the privacy issues, We propose a leak-free protocol, called SFedV, for multiparty VFL regression model training. Our approach simplifies the VFL pipeline and preserves the privacy of client data, model weights, and intermediate results, by designing special function vectors and using a quadratic MIFE scheme to compute gradients directly.

Appendix A Security Definition for MIFE

In an indistinguishability-based security game between a challenger and an adversary, the challenger runs the 𝖲𝖾𝗍𝗎𝗉𝖲𝖾𝗍𝗎𝗉\mathsf{Setup} algorithm to generate the public parameters 𝖯𝖯𝖯𝖯\mathsf{PP}, N𝑁N encryption keys 𝖤𝖪isubscript𝖤𝖪𝑖\mathsf{EK}_{i}, and master secret key 𝖬𝖲𝖪𝖬𝖲𝖪\mathsf{MSK}. The adversary then chooses the set of encryption keys that she wants. Then the adversary chooses two messages \mathbold​x0\mathboldsuperscript𝑥0\mathbold{x}^{0} and \mathbold​x1\mathboldsuperscript𝑥1\mathbold{x}^{1} and gives them to the challenger. The challenger chooses a bit β𝛽\beta at random and encrypts the message \mathbold​xβ\mathboldsuperscript𝑥𝛽\mathbold{x}^{\beta} using the ithsuperscript𝑖thi^{\text{th}} encryption key 𝖤𝖪isubscript𝖤𝖪𝑖\mathsf{EK}_{i} to get challenge ciphertext 𝖢𝖳isubscript𝖢𝖳𝑖\mathsf{CT}_{i}. The adversary then asks the challenger for the secret keys corresponding to the functions f𝑓f. At last, the adversary guesses a bit β′superscript𝛽′\beta^{\prime} and replies to the challenger. The admissible adversary wins if β′=βsuperscript𝛽′𝛽\beta^{\prime}=\beta. In security, we want the probability of the adversary winning the security game to be negligibly close to 1/2.

The adversary is said to be admissible if and only if she sends at least one element of the form (i,∗,∗)𝑖(i,*,*) in the message space and she queries the secret key for the function f𝑓f which satisfies the constraint that f​(\mathbold​x0)=f​(\mathbold​x1)𝑓\mathboldsuperscript𝑥0𝑓\mathboldsuperscript𝑥1f(\mathbold{x}^{0})=f(\mathbold{x}^{1}). We formally define MIFE security in Definition 2.

Appendix C Extension to Logistic Regression Model

In this section, we extend the protocol to work for logistic regression with the help of Taylor approximation. The prediction function of logistic models is as follows:

f​(\mathbold​x,\mathbold​w)=11−e−\mathbold​x​\mathbold​w𝑓\mathbold𝑥\mathbold𝑤11superscript𝑒\mathbold𝑥\mathbold𝑤\displaystyle f(\mathbold{x},\mathbold{w})=\frac{1}{1-e^{-\mathbold{x}\mathbold{w}}} (11)
